Hey Tony, I need a prototype of a microservices-based inventory management system that is scalable, modular, and fault-tolerant, applying Gang of Four (GoF) design patterns.

Key Requirements:
	1.	Core Microservices:
	•	Inventory Tracking Service – Monitors stock levels, updates inventory, triggers alerts.
	•	Supplier Management Service – Manages suppliers and restocking.
	•	Order Processing Service – Handles orders, updates inventory, and processes payments.
	•	Reporting Service – Generates reports on inventory, sales, and supplier performance.
	2.	Microservices Architecture:
	•	Each service operates independently with its own database.
	•	Services communicate via REST APIs or asynchronous message queues (RabbitMQ/Kafka).
	•	Scalability & Fault Tolerance – Failures in one service shouldn’t disrupt others.
	3.	GoF Design Patterns to Apply:
	•	Singleton – For shared configurations like API gateways.
	•	Factory – For creating orders, inventory alerts, supplier requests.
	•	Observer – Notifies reporting service when inventory updates.
	•	Strategy – Different restocking strategies based on demand.
	4.	Tech Stack:
	•	Backend: Java (Spring Boot) preferred.
	•	Frontend: Basic admin panel (React.js/Angular).
	•	Database: MySQL (Orders), MongoDB (Inventory).
	•	Message Broker: RabbitMQ/Kafka.
	•	API Gateway: Kong or AWS API Gateway.

Project Deliverables:
	•	Code hosted on GitHub with setup instructions.
	•	Architecture & Design Documentation.
	•	System Demo showing scalability, fault tolerance, and modularity.